{
  "doc_id": "35373",
  "text": "Besides attenuation of the cerebral inflammatory response, our findings indicated that MAPC modulated the peripheral inflammatory response, which has been implicated in the etiology of hypoxic-ischemic injury in the preterm brain [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Our results showed that MAPC prevented splenic involution. We have previously shown in the current model that splenic involution after global HI was caused by efflux of immune effector cells [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, our findings demonstrated that intravenous administration of MSC induced splenic T cell tolerance [CITATION_6] . The observed unresponsiveness of splenic T cells was associated with reduced systemic mobilization of immune effector cells and concomitant reduction of brain-infiltrating immune cells resulting in less severe inflammation in the preterm brain after global HI [CITATION_7] . Based on these findings, we postulate that MAPC therapy reduced the mobilization of immune effector cells from the spleen resulting in less extensive invasion of these injurious cells into the brain. This concept is supported by previous findings showing a spleenmediated neuroprotective effect of MAPC in traumatic CNS injury [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Recently, it was demonstrated that splenic IFNγ plays a key role in injurious signaling to the ischemic brain [CITATION_10] . Functional elimination by splenectomy or administration of IFNγ neutralizing antibodies reduced brain injury after stroke [CITATION_11] . In line with these findings, reduction of cerebral inflammation (i.e., microglial proliferation) by MAPC treatment was associated with decreased splenic IFNγ levels. To determine whether IFNγ from spleen cells is involved in preterm brain injury after global HI, temporal dynamics of splenic IFNγ release needs to be elucidated and its functional role to be determined.",
